-- South African Stocks Climb For a Third Day, Led by AVI, Bell, Mustek, RMB
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-12-15T16:23:41Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-15/south-african-shares-gain-for-third-day-led-by-avi-bcx-mustek-and-ucs.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  increased for the third day, gaining 36.97, or 0.1
percent, to 31,703.61 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, weakened for the second day, dropping 99 cents, or 0.4
percent, to 267.51 rand. Copper fell 0.5 percent, to $9,120 a
metric ton on the London Metal Exchange. Lead, zinc and tin also
declined.  AVI Ltd.  (AVI SJ), a producer and distributor of consumer
goods including food and cosmetics, snapped three days of
losses, rising 50 cents, or 1.8 percent, to 28.90 rand. The
company said per-share earnings for its continuing operations,
including capital gains and losses on the disposal of assets,
are expected to rise by between 30 percent and 40 percent in the
six months through Dec. 31 from a year ago.  Bell Equipment Ltd.  (BEL SJ), Africa’s biggest maker of
dump trucks and forklifts, climbed to the highest level in a
month, gaining 11 cents, or 1.1 percent, to 10.11 rand. Earnings
for the 12 months through December are likely to be at least 20
percent better than a year earlier, the company.  Capital Shopping Centres Group Plc  (CSO SJ), Britain’s
biggest shopping-mall owner, increased the most since Nov. 25,
jumping 1.50 rand, or 3.6 percent, to 43.75 rand. The company
rejected a 2.9 billion pounds ($4.6 billion) buy-out bid from
 Simon Property Group Inc. , the largest U.S. mall owner.  Mustek Ltd.  (MST SJ), a computer services company, surged
to the highest since February 2008, advancing 75 cents, or 18
percent, to 5 rand. The company said it received a non-binding
expression of interest that may lead to a 5.55 rand-per-share
offer from  David Kan , its chief executive officer, and Trinitas
Private Equity Fund.  Old Mutual Plc  (OML SJ), the third-biggest insurer in the
U.K., weakened to the lowest level since July, losing 0.8
percent, or 10 cents, to 12.82 rand. The insurer said it is in
talks with state regulators to obtain approvals regarding the
sale of its U.S. Life operations to affiliates of Harbinger
Capital Partners LLC and now sees the transaction closing in the
first quarter of 2011.  RMB Holdings Ltd.  (RMH SJ), a South African investment
company, rose the most since June 14, advancing 1.34 rand, or
3.8 percent, to 36.94 rand. RMB has agreed to buy  FirstRand
Ltd. ’s (FSR SJ) stake in South African property and casualty
insurer OUTsurance for 3.75 billion rand ($550 million).  UCS Group Ltd.  (UCS SJ) rallied to the highest since Oct.
2008, rising 27 cents, or 13.4 percent, to 2.29 rand. The
computer-services company said it has agreed to sell its assets
to  Business Connexion Group Ltd.  (BCX SJ) for 614.2 million
rand. Business Connexion gained 7 cents, or 1.1 percent, to 6.57
rand.  To contact the reporter on this story:
